Created 2022 for ISV Events to be consumed by Splunk.

Login to the ISV tenant and create API client_id and client_secret

If not set Set environment variable “SPLUNK_HOME” to Splunk install path
After import of app into Splunk

Navigate to settings then “Data Inputs” disable the isv_tenant_events.py script.

Now go to where the script resides, Go to install path of splunk then /etc/apps/ISVLogging/bin 

Copy the python script to a new name and edit these fields
o tokenReqURL (this is the ISV tenant url)
o client_id (from steps above)
o client_secret (from steps above)
o requestURL (this is the ISV tenant url)

**OPTIONAL** If you want to get events in from a past date, a new epoch timestamp in the checkpoint.json will need to be entered.
o C:\Program Files\Splunk\etc\apps\ISVLogging\appserver\static\checkpoint.json o https://www.epochconverter.com/ 90 days is the maximum ISV holds. *This may
bring in a lot of data* pick a date/time and copy epoch timestamp. o Edit checkpoint.json with new timestamp and save.

In Splunk go to Data Inputs, then click on “New Local Script” import the copied/modified script

Click Next and select json_no_timestamp and create a new index, select what is appropriate for your logging/indexing standards

Once this is saved
o Navigate to Apps
o ISVLogging o Click Edit
o Click Source
o Do a search of “index=” and replace the value with NEW index name created in previous step. SAVE (all these dashboards were written specifically on default isv logging index created on install)

You should now start to see data on the dashboard.


